// ─── FAQ (PAA-sourced; mirrored into FAQPage schema) ───
const faqs = [
  { q: "What does captive-bred mean for African Grey parrots?",
    a: "Captive-bred means the bird was hatched from parents already living in legal captivity and raised entirely in an aviary — never taken from the wild. Here at C.A.Gs, every Congo and Timneh Grey is hatched in our USDA-licensed Midland, Texas home and hand-fed by our family from a few weeks old.\n\nBecause the African Grey (Psittacus erithacus) is listed on CITES Appendix I, a captive-bred bird carries Appendix I documentation, a closed band, and a hatch certificate proving it was aviary-raised, not wild-caught." },
  { q: "Are C.A.Gs African Greys captive-bred?",
    a: "Yes — 100%. Every Grey we place is U.S. captive-bred and hand-raised in our home, never wild-caught and never imported.\n\nWe can prove it for the specific bird you reserve with a CITES Appendix I captive-bred certificate, a closed band number, a hatch certificate, a PCR DNA sexing certificate, and a board-certified avian-vet health certificate. You receive that paperwork before any deposit changes hands." },
  { q: "Is it legal to own a captive-bred African Grey in the USA?",
    a: "Yes. African Greys were uplisted to CITES Appendix I at CoP17 (effective January 2017), which bans commercial trade in wild-caught birds — but captive-bred African Greys are legal to own and transfer domestically within the United States with proper documentation.\n\nThe closed band and hatch certificate that travel with every C.A.Gs Grey establish its captive-bred origin, so your ownership rests on solid legal ground." },
  { q: "Are captive-bred African Greys better pets than wild-caught birds?",
    a: "Significantly. A hand-raised captive-bred Grey is socialized to people during the critical first 12–16 weeks of life, so it is calmer, more trainable, and far more likely to talk.\n\nWild-caught birds are traumatized by capture and transport, often never fully tame, and frequently carry diseases such as psittacosis that can infect other birds in the home.\n\nBeyond the welfare difference, importing a wild-caught African Grey into the USA is illegal — so a captive-bred bird is the only ethical and lawful choice." },
  { q: "How can I tell if an African Grey is really captive-bred and not wild-caught?",
    a: "Ask for the documents and check the band. A genuinely captive-bred Grey has a seamless closed band (slipped on as a chick and impossible to fit on an adult), an individual CITES Appendix I captive-bred certificate, and a hatch certificate naming the breeder.\n\nA verifiable USDA Animal Welfare Act license is the final tell. If a seller cannot produce a CITES certificate for that exact bird — not a generic letter — treat it as a red flag and read our guide to avoiding African Grey scams before paying." },
  { q: "Why does buying captive-bred help wild African Grey populations?",
    a: "Wild African Grey numbers have fallen sharply across West and Central Africa, which is exactly why the species was moved to CITES Appendix I and is now listed as Endangered.\n\nChoosing a documented captive-bred bird removes any incentive to poach from the wild — every dollar that goes to a licensed captive breeder is a dollar that does not fund trapping.\n\nBuying captive-bred protects both your future companion and the wild flocks it descends from." },
];

