    <section id="what-it-means" class="scroll-mt-20 py-14 px-4 md:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto">
        <div class="mb-6 border-l-4 border-green pl-4">
          <p class="text-clay font-sora text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-widest mb-2">Definition</p>
          <h2 class="font-lora font-bold text-logo-dark">What Does "Captive-Bred" Actually Mean?</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4 text-stone-600 leading-relaxed text-[15px]" style="max-width:70ch;">
          <p>A captive-bred African Grey is a bird that was hatched from parents already living in legal captivity and raised entirely inside an aviary — it has never been taken from the wild, never been illegally trapped, and never crossed a border in a smuggler's crate.</p>
          <p>The African Grey (<em>Psittacus erithacus</em>) is native to the rainforests of West and Central Africa, and as <a href="https://parrots.org/encyclopedia/grey-parrot/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">the World Parrot Trust species encyclopedia</a> documents, decades of trapping for the pet trade pushed wild populations into steep decline.</p>
          <p>Captive breeding exists precisely so that families can keep this remarkable parrot without touching a single wild bird.</p>
          <p>Here at C.A.Gs, captive-bred is not a marketing word — it is our entire operation. Every Congo and Timneh Grey we place is hatched in our Midland, Texas home, hand-fed by our family from a few weeks old, and weaned under our roof.</p>
          <p>Because we slip a seamless <strong>closed band</strong> onto each chick's leg in its first weeks, that band physically cannot be added to a wild adult later — it is permanent, tamper-evident proof of where and when the bird was hatched.</p>
          <p>Pair that band with a hatch certificate and an individual CITES Appendix I certificate, and the bird's captive-bred origin is documented from the first day of its life.</p>
          <p>This matters legally as much as it matters ethically. African Greys were uplisted to <a href="https://cites.org/eng/app/appendices.php" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">CITES Appendix I</a> at CoP17, effective January 2017, which bans commercial trade in wild-caught birds worldwide.</p>
          <p>A captive-bred Grey, by contrast, is legal to own and transfer domestically in the United States with proper documentation — which is exactly why the paperwork detailed on our <a href="/cites-african-grey-documentation/">CITES documentation guide</a> travels with every Grey we sell.</p>
          <h3 class="font-sora font-bold text-sm uppercase tracking-wide text-green mt-5 mb-1.5">How Can You Verify a Closed Band Yourself?</h3>
          <p>Run a finger around the band before you pay anything. A genuine closed band is one seamless ring with no gap, hinge, or solder line — it slid over a chick's foot in its first weeks and physically cannot be fitted to an adult bird.</p>
          <p>If you feel a split or see a clamp mark, you are looking at an open band, which proves nothing about origin.</p>
          <h4 class="font-sora font-bold text-[13px] uppercase tracking-wide text-clay-ink mt-3 mb-1">What Should the Band Tell You?</h4>
          <p>Ours carry an identifier we record at banding, and we read it back to you on a live video call with the bird in frame — so the band you inspect on arrival is the band you saw before your deposit.</p>
          <h5 class="font-sora font-bold text-[12px] uppercase tracking-wide text-green mt-2.5 mb-1">Match the Band to the Hatch Certificate</h5>
          <p>The band number must match the hatch certificate and the CITES paperwork word for word.</p>
          <h6 class="font-sora font-bold text-[11px] uppercase tracking-wide text-clay-ink mt-2.5 mb-1">One Mismatch Is One Too Many</h6>
          <p>Walk away, and read our <a href="/how-to-avoid-african-grey-parrot-scams/">scam-prevention guide</a> before you contact another seller.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 5b. CAPTIVE-BRED VS WILD-CAUGHT (custom compare) -->
    <section id="vs-wild-caught" class="scroll-mt-20 bg-cream py-14 px-4 md:py-16">
      <div class="max-w-5xl mx-auto">
        <div class="mb-7 border-l-4 border-green pl-4">
